  "texts": [
    "In terms of the effectiveness of the model, this model can effectively handle sequential data with both spatial and temporal dependencies, and can leverage multiple sources of input features to improve performance.",
    "CNNs can extract useful features from the input data by identifying patterns in the spatial dimensions, such as extracting useful information from student's academic records (course names and course descriptions), whereas LSTMs are effective in modeling sequential data by capturing temporal dependencies in the input data, such as modeling student's academic history (courses taken and grades earned).",
    "For further enhancing the performance, this hybrid model can be expanded to include additional input variables, such as student demographic and behavioral data.",
    "In Xiong et al (2022), CNN was combined with RNN for early prediction of student performance before the beginning of the course (the demographic data were used to train the CNN for extracting useful features, and then the CNN's output was used as a feature vector to feed into the RNN in order to predict the student performance).",
    "This means that the model depends on the information available at that time to predict the student performance after a specific length of time, such as at the start of a course or semester."
